insecticides worldwide.

00:34:26.900 --> 00:34:29.380 align:middle line:84%
These neonicotinoids,
which are neurotoxic,

00:34:29.380 --> 00:34:32.620 align:middle line:84%
they target the nervous system,
affect the ability of bees

00:34:32.620 --> 00:34:35.350 align:middle line:84%
to learn, and to remember,
and to navigate, all of which

00:34:35.350 --> 00:34:38.440 align:middle line:84%
would contribute to an
inability to return to the hive

00:34:38.440 --> 00:34:40.630 align:middle line:90%
after foraging.

00:34:40.630 --> 00:34:42.130 align:middle line:90%
Bees are gleaners.

00:34:42.130 --> 00:34:44.440 align:middle line:84%
Bees are particularly
vulnerable,

00:34:44.440 --> 00:34:48.320 align:middle line:84%
because they're really designed
to pick up small particles.

00:34:48.320 --> 00:34:51.310 align:middle line:84%
They're built to
electrostatically attract

00:34:51.310 --> 00:34:53.980 align:middle line:90%
pollen.

00:34:53.980 --> 00:34:56.320 align:middle line:84%
We recently discovered,
with the sequencing

00:34:56.320 --> 00:34:59.860 align:middle line:84%
of the entire honeybee
genome, honeybees

00:34:59.860 --> 00:35:01.990 align:middle line:84%
are distinctly
lacking enzymes that

00:35:01.990 --> 00:35:04.730 align:middle line:90%
break down poisons or toxins.

00:35:04.730 --> 00:35:27.960 align:middle line:90%
>> [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:35:27.960 --> 00:35:33.000 align:middle line:84%
>> In Europe, bees are
completely dependent on human

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:37.560 align:middle line:90%
care and on human help.

00:35:37.560 --> 00:35:42.600 align:middle line:84%
Without this care, many,
many bee colonies will die,

00:35:42.600 --> 00:35:47.280 align:middle line:84%
and only very few will
survive without the help

00:35:47.280 --> 00:35:51.640 align:middle line:84%
of the beekeepers
and all human beings.

00:35:51.640 --> 00:35:57.250 align:middle line:84%
In former times, the coal
miners had special birds

00:35:57.250 --> 00:35:59.260 align:middle line:90%
in the coal mines.

00:35:59.260 --> 00:36:05.620 align:middle line:84%
And when the canary birds
stopped singing and stayed

00:36:05.620 --> 00:36:12.226 align:middle line:84%
silent, it was time for the coal
miners to leave the mountain.

00:36:12.226 --> 00:36:23.050 align:middle line:90%


00:36:23.050 --> 00:36:24.940 align:middle line:84%
>> What most people
think of when they think

00:36:24.940 --> 00:36:27.340 align:middle line:84%
of a pollinator, is they
think of the honeybee.

00:36:27.340 --> 00:36:29.650 align:middle line:84%
And the honeybee is by
far the most important

00:36:29.650 --> 00:36:31.990 align:middle line:90%
agricultural pollinator we have.

00:36:31.990 --> 00:36:35.230 align:middle line:84%
But what a lot of people
don't realize is number one,

00:36:35.230 --> 00:36:38.230 align:middle line:84%
we have about 4,000
species of other bees.

00:36:38.230 --> 00:36:40.930 align:middle line:84%
Everything from
large bumblebees,

00:36:40.930 --> 00:36:44.080 align:middle line:84%
thousands of
species of bees that

00:36:44.080 --> 00:36:48.050 align:middle line:84%
are everything from little
bees, they look like flies,

00:36:48.050 --> 00:36:52.120 align:middle line:84%
to bright green,
fluorescent almost, green,

00:36:52.120 --> 00:36:55.600 align:middle line:90%
to striped in different colors.

00:36:55.600 --> 00:36:59.530 align:middle line:84%
Bees of all varieties
across the world.

00:36:59.530 --> 00:37:05.530 align:middle line:84%
Beyond bees, flies and beetles
are very, very important

00:37:05.530 --> 00:37:07.240 align:middle line:90%
pollinators.

00:37:07.240 --> 00:37:12.100 align:middle line:84%
>> The beauty of the seed is out
of one, you can get millions.

00:37:12.100 --> 00:37:15.340 align:middle line:84%
The beauty of the pollinator,
is it turns that one

00:37:15.340 --> 00:37:17.050 align:middle line:90%
into the million.

00:37:17.050 --> 00:37:19.570 align:middle line:84%
And that's an
economics of sharing.

00:37:19.570 --> 00:37:22.000 align:middle line:84%
That's, to me, the real
economics of growth,

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:23.740 align:middle line:90%
because life is growing.

00:37:23.740 --> 00:37:26.530 align:middle line:90%


00:37:26.530 --> 00:37:28.660 align:middle line:84%
>> Without the pollinators,
we'd lose the plants.

00:37:28.660 --> 00:37:30.322 align:middle line:84%
They're just
completely codependent.

00:37:30.322 --> 00:37:32.530 align:middle line:84%
The pollinators wouldn't be
there without the plants,

00:37:32.530 --> 00:37:35.200 align:middle line:84%
and the plants wouldn't be
there without the pollinators.

00:37:35.200 --> 00:37:38.830 align:middle line:84%
>> We've seen a decline
in many of our bees.

00:37:38.830 --> 00:37:43.660 align:middle line:84%
With our native bees, we're
seeing declines, probably

00:37:43.660 --> 00:37:44.920 align:middle line:90%
from the same things.

00:37:44.920 --> 00:37:48.730 align:middle line:84%
Disease, to nutrition, to
potentially pesticides,

00:37:48.730 --> 00:37:52.000 align:middle line:90%
as well as habitat loss.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:56.010 align:middle line:84%
>> So if bees are dying, we can
be sure that butterflies will

00:37:56.010 --> 00:37:59.070 align:middle line:84%
be dying, solitary
bees will be dying,

00:37:59.070 --> 00:38:00.720 align:middle line:90%
bumblebees will be dying.

00:38:00.720 --> 00:38:04.950 align:middle line:84%
And we know from the point of
conventional academic ecology

00:38:04.950 --> 00:38:08.520 align:middle line:84%
that if insects are dying,
birds will be dying,

00:38:08.520 --> 00:38:10.380 align:middle line:90%
plants will be dying.

00:38:10.380 --> 00:38:12.540 align:middle line:84%
>> I think we're doing
some pretty scary things,

00:38:12.540 --> 00:38:14.070 align:middle line:84%
and the situation
is pretty dire.

00:38:14.070 --> 00:38:17.940 align:middle line:84%
And I think we're just beginning
to realize how dire it is.

00:38:17.940 --> 00:38:20.525 align:middle line:84%
But at the same
time, nature comes up

00:38:20.525 --> 00:38:22.650 align:middle line:84%
with all sorts of surprises,
and hopefully there'll

00:38:22.650 --> 00:38:27.240 align:middle line:84%
be some cheering surprises
rather than all gloomy ones.

00:38:27.240 --> 00:38:29.790 align:middle line:84%
>> These little
guys run the world.

00:38:29.790 --> 00:38:33.300 align:middle line:84%
These guys really
are the bosses.

00:38:33.300 --> 00:38:35.310 align:middle line:84%
They're doing all
of our work for us,

00:38:35.310 --> 00:38:37.180 align:middle line:84%
and without them, we'd
be in big trouble.

00:38:37.180 --> 00:38:46.126 align:middle line:90%


00:38:46.126 --> 00:38:49.108 align:middle line:90%
[BEES BUZZING]

00:38:49.108 --> 00:38:57.580 align:middle line:90%


00:38:57.580 --> 00:39:00.640 align:middle line:84%
>> This honey that I'm
collecting here at the moment,

00:39:00.640 --> 00:39:04.020 align:middle line:84%
here from the west coast of
South Island in New Zealand,

00:39:04.020 --> 00:39:07.660 align:middle line:84%
is some the cleanest
honey in the world.

00:39:07.660 --> 00:39:09.100 align:middle line:90%
I am a honey robber.

00:39:09.100 --> 00:39:11.560 align:middle line:84%
I steal their
honey, because what

00:39:11.560 --> 00:39:14.560 align:middle line:84%
they bring in is what
they use for the winter.

00:39:14.560 --> 00:39:16.480 align:middle line:84%
So we actually
steal their honey.

00:39:16.480 --> 00:39:18.850 align:middle line:84%
We actually rob their
honey, but leave enough

00:39:18.850 --> 00:39:20.150 align:middle line:90%
so the bees survive the winter.

00:39:20.150 --> 00:39:25.150 align:middle line:90%


00:39:25.150 --> 00:39:27.050 align:middle line:90%
I'm an organic beekeeper.

00:39:27.050 --> 00:39:29.590 align:middle line:84%
And the reason is mainly
what I believe in.

00:39:29.590 --> 00:39:31.380 align:middle line:90%
It's from the heart.

00:39:31.380 --> 00:39:33.130 align:middle line:84%
It's not from the
dollars point of view.

00:39:33.130 --> 00:39:33.963 align:middle line:90%
It's from the heart.

00:39:33.963 --> 00:39:44.150 align:middle line:90%


00:39:44.150 --> 00:39:47.240 align:middle line:84%
The bees are dying,
and I personally

00:39:47.240 --> 00:39:49.790 align:middle line:90%
think it's genetic modification.

00:39:49.790 --> 00:39:51.560 align:middle line:90%
I personally think that.

00:39:51.560 --> 00:39:53.380 align:middle line:84%
We're changing the
structure of the plant.

00:39:53.380 --> 00:39:55.672 align:middle line:84%
the structure of the plant
is being changed completely,

00:39:55.672 --> 00:39:57.720 align:middle line:84%
and the bees are
telling us that.

00:39:57.720 --> 00:40:01.310 align:middle line:84%
The bees are dying
because of it.

00:40:01.310 --> 00:40:04.190 align:middle line:84%
>> You take genes from
an unrelated species,

00:40:04.190 --> 00:40:08.270 align:middle line:84%
and shoot it into
the cells of a plant.

00:40:08.270 --> 00:40:12.110 align:middle line:84%
And there are only two ways you
can introduce unrelated genes.

00:40:12.110 --> 00:40:14.810 align:middle line:84%
The first is the use
of a gene gun, where

00:40:14.810 --> 00:40:18.710 align:middle line:84%
you shoot gold particles
laden with genes

00:40:18.710 --> 00:40:21.070 align:middle line:90%
and put them into the organism.

00:40:21.070 --> 00:40:22.610 align:middle line:84%
But it's a very
unreliable process,

00:40:22.610 --> 00:40:25.820 align:middle line:84%
so you also have to add
antibiotic resistance markers.

00:40:25.820 --> 00:40:28.430 align:middle line:84%
You also have to
add viral promoters.

00:40:28.430 --> 00:40:30.800 align:middle line:84%
And every genetically
engineered seed

00:40:30.800 --> 00:40:36.810 align:middle line:84%
is a bundle of bacteria,
toxins, viral promoters.

00:40:36.810 --> 00:40:38.880 align:middle line:84%
>> Genetically modified
organisms are planted

00:40:38.880 --> 00:40:42.930 align:middle line:84%
in millions of acres
around the United States.

00:40:42.930 --> 00:40:46.590 align:middle line:84%
Genetically engineered
crops can compromise

00:40:46.590 --> 00:40:49.740 align:middle line:90%
the immune system of bees.

00:40:49.740 --> 00:40:53.220 align:middle line:84%
One German scientist found
that when bees collect pollen

00:40:53.220 --> 00:40:57.480 align:middle line:84%
from corn, the genes that have
been inserted into the corn

00:40:57.480 --> 00:41:01.260 align:middle line:84%
end up transferring into the
gut microorganisms of the bees

00:41:01.260 --> 00:41:02.860 align:middle line:90%
and continue to function.

00:41:02.860 --> 00:41:05.100 align:middle line:84%
Unfortunately, human
beings also get

00:41:05.100 --> 00:41:07.570 align:middle line:84%
genes transferred to
their gut bacteria,

00:41:07.570 --> 00:41:10.140 align:middle line:84%
meaning it produces this
genetically engineered bacteria

00:41:10.140 --> 00:41:12.390 align:middle line:90%
inside of us.

00:41:12.390 --> 00:41:17.790 align:middle line:84%
>> When we start to
manipulate genetic material,

00:41:17.790 --> 00:41:21.600 align:middle line:84%
we are going to the
very deepest sources,

00:41:21.600 --> 00:41:23.910 align:middle line:84%
to the very deepest
layers of the human being.

00:41:23.910 --> 00:41:27.310 align:middle line:90%


00:41:27.310 --> 00:41:31.190 align:middle line:84%
It allows us to
be almost godlike.

00:41:31.190 --> 00:41:36.550 align:middle line:84%
But the question is, do we
have the wisdom, the morality,

00:41:36.550 --> 00:41:40.040 align:middle line:84%
the depth, to do
these interventions?

00:41:40.040 --> 00:41:43.460 align:middle line:84%
Are we really knowing
what we are doing?

00:41:43.460 --> 00:41:48.650 align:middle line:84%
Are we sure that what we do
will not have long-term effects?

00:41:48.650 --> 00:41:53.930 align:middle line:84%
And we are not experimenting
here with animals or plants.

00:41:53.930 --> 00:41:56.060 align:middle line:84%
We are experimenting
with the human being.

00:41:56.060 --> 00:41:58.730 align:middle line:90%


00:41:58.730 --> 00:42:03.480 align:middle line:84%
With the soul of human beings,
with the body of human beings.

00:42:03.480 --> 00:42:08.930 align:middle line:84%
Nature is very patient
for a long time,

00:42:08.930 --> 00:42:13.910 align:middle line:84%
but there is a moment
when things do collapse.

00:42:13.910 --> 00:42:16.760 align:middle line:84%
We have to wake up, and
hopefully wake up early enough

00:42:16.760 --> 00:42:17.565 align:middle line:90%
to make a change.

00:42:17.565 --> 00:42:24.880 align:middle line:90%


00:42:24.880 --> 00:42:29.560 align:middle line:84%
>> I became a beekeeper in
2003 under rather unusual

00:42:29.560 --> 00:42:30.520 align:middle line:90%
circumstances.

00:42:30.520 --> 00:42:33.970 align:middle line:84%
I'd been invited by the
local beekeeping association

00:42:33.970 --> 00:42:36.790 align:middle line:84%
to give them a talk on genetic
engineering in relation

00:42:36.790 --> 00:42:38.770 align:middle line:90%
to bees.

00:42:38.770 --> 00:42:43.510 align:middle line:84%
And one of them said, why don't
you come and look at our bees?

00:42:43.510 --> 00:42:47.020 align:middle line:84%
And then we opened some bee
hives, and that's what did it.

00:42:47.020 --> 00:42:48.105 align:middle line:90%
I was absolutely smitten.

00:42:48.105 --> 00:42:50.930 align:middle line:90%


00:42:50.930 --> 00:42:52.840 align:middle line:84%
One of the biggest
challenges to beekeepers

00:42:52.840 --> 00:42:56.980 align:middle line:84%
was the varroa mite, which has
now spread all over the United

00:42:56.980 --> 00:42:58.240 align:middle line:90%
Kingdom.

00:42:58.240 --> 00:43:00.250 align:middle line:84%
It's a little beast
that lives on the bee

00:43:00.250 --> 00:43:02.530 align:middle line:90%
and drinks its blood.

00:43:02.530 --> 00:43:07.600 align:middle line:84%
And beekeepers have found that
unless they treat their bees

00:43:07.600 --> 00:43:10.420 align:middle line:84%
with chemicals every
year, they will

00:43:10.420 --> 00:43:13.790 align:middle line:90%
be killed by the varroa mite.

00:43:13.790 --> 00:43:16.280 align:middle line:84%
I was taught the conventional
way of beekeeping,

00:43:16.280 --> 00:43:18.350 align:middle line:84%
and did all the
things that my mentors

00:43:18.350 --> 00:43:21.940 align:middle line:84%
taught me, which includes
putting chemicals in the hive.

00:43:21.940 --> 00:43:26.670 align:middle line:84%
The chemicals I started with
was a synthetic pyrethroid

00:43:26.670 --> 00:43:27.470 align:middle line:90%
called Apistan.

00:43:27.470 --> 00:43:30.170 align:middle line:90%


00:43:30.170 --> 00:43:34.710 align:middle line:84%
Clearly, one doesn't want
that sort of thing in honey.

00:43:34.710 --> 00:43:36.750 align:middle line:84%
I was going down a road
which didn't really

00:43:36.750 --> 00:43:38.860 align:middle line:90%
fit with my outlook.

00:43:38.860 --> 00:43:40.830 align:middle line:84%
In fact, if you get
the dosage wrong,

00:43:40.830 --> 00:43:43.665 align:middle line:84%
you get bee mortality from
the anti-varroa chemicals

00:43:43.665 --> 00:43:45.390 align:middle line:90%
that you use.

00:43:45.390 --> 00:43:48.930 align:middle line:84%
You are on a kind of
treadmill of putting chemicals

00:43:48.930 --> 00:43:50.200 align:middle line:90%
in the hives.

00:43:50.200 --> 00:43:56.640 align:middle line:84%
You're postponing the day when
the bee adapts to the mite.

00:43:56.640 --> 00:43:59.550 align:middle line:84%
>> In the process of trying
to kill the mites for so long,

00:43:59.550 --> 00:44:04.380 align:middle line:84%
and using so many chemicals,
we're breeding mites that adapt

00:44:04.380 --> 00:44:07.980 align:middle line:84%
faster and faster to every
new chemical we throw at them.

00:44:07.980 --> 00:44:11.730 align:middle line:84%
This deadly chemical coumaphos
has no effect whatsoever

00:44:11.730 --> 00:44:12.750 align:middle line:90%
on the varroa mite.

00:44:12.750 --> 00:44:16.530 align:middle line:84%
In fact, the varroa mite
treated with the coumaphos

00:44:16.530 --> 00:44:20.730 align:middle line:84%
did better by some measures than
mites that were not treated.

00:44:20.730 --> 00:44:24.540 align:middle line:84%
So in other words, a
chemical that was formerly

00:44:24.540 --> 00:44:28.440 align:middle line:84%
a deadly poison to them
is now somehow being

00:44:28.440 --> 00:44:31.650 align:middle line:90%
used as a resource.

00:44:31.650 --> 00:44:33.630 align:middle line:84%
They're becoming
stronger and stronger.

00:44:33.630 --> 00:44:35.640 align:middle line:84%
We've bred a race
of super mites.

00:44:35.640 --> 00:44:39.570 align:middle line:90%


00:44:39.570 --> 00:44:43.600 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm keeping the Warre hive
to see if the bees can survive

00:44:43.600 --> 00:44:48.950 align:middle line:84%
with varroa without any
intervention with chemicals.

00:44:48.950 --> 00:44:52.780 align:middle line:84%
This method of keeping
bees without any chemicals

00:44:52.780 --> 00:44:55.840 align:middle line:84%
runs the risk of going
for broke, definitely.

00:44:55.840 --> 00:44:58.240 align:middle line:84%
You could lose
all your colonies.

00:44:58.240 --> 00:45:01.570 align:middle line:84%
But if you are
interfering, you're

00:45:01.570 --> 00:45:04.410 align:middle line:90%
going against natural selection.

00:45:04.410 --> 00:45:07.030 align:middle line:84%
OK, this is a
Darwinian approach,

00:45:07.030 --> 00:45:09.100 align:middle line:84%
but the only other
alternative is

00:45:09.100 --> 00:45:13.900 align:middle line:84%
to stay on the treadmill of
giving chemicals year in,

00:45:13.900 --> 00:45:14.920 align:middle line:90%
year out, forever.

00:45:14.920 --> 00:45:17.660 align:middle line:90%


00:45:17.660 --> 00:45:22.690 align:middle line:84%
In this new type of hive, the
bee might be in a better home

00:45:22.690 --> 00:45:27.310 align:middle line:84%
to defend itself against the
ravages of the varroa mite.

00:45:27.310 --> 00:45:30.070 align:middle line:84%
I'm leaving the bee and
the mite more or less

00:45:30.070 --> 00:45:32.730 align:middle line:90%
to fight it out together.

00:45:32.730 --> 00:45:36.340 align:middle line:84%
And that is, I think, the
goal in long-term sustainable

00:45:36.340 --> 00:45:40.540 align:middle line:84%
beekeeping, is to let bee
and mite coevolve together.

00:45:40.540 --> 00:45:46.738 align:middle line:90%


